Here's how to implement all three:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button** — in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

The `Command` intercepts the button tap so you can show a dialog instead of navigating immediately:

```csharp
// In EditProductViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**2. Guard the hardware/swipe back** — override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell.xaml.cs` to catch system-initiated back navigation (hardware back button, swipe gesture) that bypasses your custom button:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back (Pop) navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // stay on page

        deferral.Complete(); // always call this
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async work in `OnNavigating` — without it the navigation completes before your `await` finishes.
- Always call `deferral.Complete()` (even after cancel) to avoid deadlocking Shell.
- Filter on `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so you only guard *back* navigation, not forward pushes.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the visible button; `OnNavigating` handles hardware/gesture back.
